WOW!! What a phenomenal unexpected encounter! Drove into a small lot away from the many people here today and there was a Pileated Woodpecker sitting near the ground picking away at a rotting tree stump. The car rolled right up to it and when I stopped right next to it, it didn't take off. I've never seen such a daring Pileated Woodpecker before, they tend to be very, very shy with letting people approach them. I snapped some amazing pictures! The fun ended when a person walked into the parking lot and the Pileated Woodpecker fled. Can't believe how cooperative he was!!

A hard run to their location like Homer Simpson chasing a donut (huffing and puffing and all) led to “it just flew” (d’oh!) but fortunately Mary Normandia, who had no desire to run at the pace I set, spotted it shortly thereafter at the south end of the gully. A gorgeous male, it called at least twice and pounded the hell out of a couple of tree trunks before disappearing in a general southerly direction. Lots of photos. Thank you jeebus.

Shortly after I arrived, while walking downstream of pad D I saw a very large bird being chased by a smaller bird, they flew right over me very quickly.  When it registered to me that the "small" bird was an acorn woodpecker, and thinking that I saw a crest on the larger bird, I got very excited.  About 10 minutes later I heard very loud hammering and came across the pileated in a tree concentrating intently on one spot (presumably ants or termites inside).  She stayed in the same tree for all four hours (I left for a bit and came back), though moved around a bit at the end.  Female, got very nice looks and photos, and a couple short recordings of calls that I will upload later.

Male. Heard calling from Circle Dr Entrance Trail. Second guessed myself and decided not to mark it down but then eventually re-heard and finally seen. Probably my most incredible experience with this bird. I was looking for it after I saw it and all of a sudden I heard and felt this woosh of air over my head. I looked forward to see that the Pileated had just flown about two feet over my head and landed about 12 ft away three ft off the ground. The bird than spent about 25 minutes foraging on this tree going into the ground many times and allowing very close approaches. The bird than proceeded to move intermittently between trees staying very close to the base of the trunk each time! As if things couldn’t get more incredible, on my return trip, Sean found the male exact sting a nest which was amazing!!

Pair of pileated- I’ve only seen singles before this. I noticed them fly together to a tree near me. I tracked them for about 10 minutes as they moved up and down a tree, circling, pecking the tree, eyeing each other, approaching to within an inch or two, then flying to another tree to repeat this. I’d initially thought they were male and female. Looking at my photos, they are both female (no red cheek stripe)- makes me wonder if this was either a territorial display (not aggressive) or if they were each trying to attract a male who was out of sight.

Observation Details: Amazing watching these two! Sudden explosion of woodpeckers everywhere in one spot. Watched them foraging, calling, and hopping around together, then after a while, male approached the female with rest raised moving his head about, then mounted her, then hopped over to the other side with the same display. Have photos.

Observation Details: Shortly after I arrived, while walking downstream of pad D I saw a very large bird being chased by a smaller bird, they flew right over me very quickly.  When it registered to me that the "small" bird was an acorn woodpecker, and thinking that I saw a crest on the larger bird, I got very excited.  About 10 minutes later I heard very loud hammering and came across the pileated in a tree concentrating intently on one spot (presumably ants or termites inside).  She stayed in the same tree for all four hours (I left for a bit and came back), though moved around a bit at the end.  Female, got very nice looks and photos, and a couple short recordings of calls that I will upload later.

Ginormous unmistakeable woodpecker. Long-awaited county bird after fruitlessly chasing four over the last several years. Found several days ago, refound yesterday by Karlo Mirth, and refound again today by Bobby and Coleen Veltri. A hard run to their location like Homer Simpson chasing a donut (huffing and puffing and all) led to “it just flew” (d’oh!) but fortunately Mary Normandia, who had no desire to run at the pace I set, spotted it shortly thereafter at the south end of the gully. A gorgeous male, it called at least twice and pounded the hell out of a couple of tree trunks before disappearing in a general southerly direction. Lots of photos. Thank you jeebus.

Seen at close range for 15 minutes near the intersection of East Ridge and Philips Loop trails. It as doing territorial drumming on a Monterey Pine: I had inadvertently left my video recording in my shirt pocket so captured about 12 minutes of or most of the territorial drumming of the male.  There we're 14 drumming episodes that each took less than two seconds, with about twenty plus hits to the wood in the drumming period. Drumming occurring with regular intervals, with the average interval of 79 seconds, with a minim of 27 sec. and max of 267, but most were about 77, 72, 88 seconds. Seems like the bird operates in 25 seconds time increments, building on the period or subtracting from it.   The Pileated was chased off by an Acorn Woodpecker.

Observation Details: Heard and then observed one land on a tree at these coordinates (not on the trail): 39.16802, -119.92274. Watched it call and get a response from a second, quite far off. Then saw two together later near where the lower trail peters out. They were in the area for 20-30 minutes before I left, and I refound them several times. One male and one female-type. I witnessed the male feeding the female-type (see crappy photo), which made me think the second could be a juvenile, but I'm now thinking it could be courtship behavior. That said, I did think at one point that there might be three--maybe a pair and a juvenile--but they were moving around a lot so I'm not confident there were more than just the two. Thanks to Clayton for the tips!

Observation Details: Continuing bird constructing nest on snag near Trail's End sign on the Stream Trail. Male, black and white face with red malar stripe, red crown, and black back, larger than other woodpeckers. Fully inside nest hole standing upside down and working on bottom. Pauses periodically to expel wood chips. Photos. Observed from 10:10am to 11am when bird flew off. Returned to nest at 1145am; I left shortly thereafter. There were a number of other observers, including George Peyton and Dave Quady. Photos show full bird outside of the nest, the bird fully within the nest and working upside down drilling at the bottom, and expelling some of the debris.

But it quickly became apparent that one, the parent, was doing all the "shopping"......and the other was a juvenille who was curious and a bit leary of his new world.....and just wanted the parent to forage and feed him. The juvenille had no interest whatever in watching and learning to forage! So next time you enter the trail from either entrance at the parking lot...check out the wooden fence rails...quite a few Pileated Woodpecker holes on both sides!

Observation Details: Heard and then observed one land on a tree at these coordinates (not on the trail): 39.16802, -119.92274. Watched it call and get a response from a second, quite far off. Then saw two together later near where the lower trail peters out. They were in the area for 20-30 minutes before I left, and I refound them several times. One male and one female-type. I witnessed the male feeding the female-type (see crappy photo), which made me think the second could be a juvenile, but I'm now thinking it could be courtship behavior. That said, I did think at one point that there might be three--maybe a pair and a juvenile--but they were moving around a lot so I'm not confident there were more than just the two. Thanks to Clayton for the tips!

Observation Details: I got good views of two birds roughly 1/4 apart.  The first was a male, feeding on a log near the top of the river bluff.  The second was a female, feeding along trees that lined a side creek.  Neither was particularly friendly, but a did manage a couple of long range shots of the female.  I also spoke to another birder who had photographed them earlier this spring.  I listened to them call back and forth to one another for the better part of an hour and believe that they are resident to these woods.  Will be fun to follow and see if young birds appear later this summer.

This has positively encouraged nesting/feeding on our acreage. This tree was no exception. Our faller made a some scars on it, removing a bit of the bark. This morning was awesome watching this male Pileated Woodpecker hammer away at the tree, gouging out the wood....this morning he left a hole about 2.5" high/wide and approx. 3/4" deep [maybe deeper, hard to tell from the ground]. Neat to see this.

Amazing watching these two! Sudden explosion of woodpeckers everywhere in one spot. Watched them foraging, calling, and hopping around together, then after a while, male approached the female with rest raised moving his head about, then mounted her, then hopped over to the other side with the same display. Then they both stood there for a bit silently together, then continued on foraging and calling. Female looks younger, but not completely immature, and had quite a lot of yellow on her crest. Have photos.

Two males (red moustaches) on same palm tree, appeared to be engaged in some type of coordinated behavior.  One on each side of the palm trunk, at the same height above the ground. They would both repel down the trunk in step-wise fashion...first one would drop about a foot down then the other bird would do the same. We are used to seeing these birds move from tree to tree quickly and gone before we have enough time to observe and photograph, but these two were focused, sticking to the one tree for a few minutes, and not being bothered by us making close approach.

Observation Details: Male was working on a nest cavity in a large tree deeper in the woods. The female was foraging close to the fence-line where I was able to get some shots.

Female eating home made suet from the wooden suet cage. She stayed about 4 minutes. She carefully checked the sky and perches around her frequently as she ate. I have read that Pileated Woodpeckers can live to be 9 to 12 years old. What I have observed myself is that the Pileateds in my yard, are very careful to constantly understand who might be in their environment. They are always paying attention and making frequent observations by scanning the yard, the skies and the tree perches as shown in the photos that accompany this observation. You can see her turning her head and looking in all directions.  I have even seen them warn each other when a flock of crows enters the area. So I wonder if their longevity might have something to do with their alertness, and ability to observe what is going on around them, as well as their strong pair bond, and willingness to warn each other if danger approaches.

Observation Details: Heard and then observed one land on a tree at these coordinates (not on the trail): 39.16802, -119.92274. Watched it call and get a response from a second, quite far off. Then saw two together later near where the lower trail peters out. They were in the area for 20-30 minutes before I left, and I refound them several times. One male and one female-type. I witnessed the male feeding the female-type (see crappy photo), which made me think the second could be a juvenile, but I'm now thinking it could be courtship behavior. That said, I did think at one point that there might be three--maybe a pair and a juvenile--but they were moving around a lot so I'm not confident there were more than just the two. Thanks to Clayton for the tips!

Male. Heard calling from Circle Dr Entrance Trail. Second guessed myself and decided not to mark it down but then eventually re-heard and finally seen. Probably my most incredible experience with this bird. I was looking for it after I saw it and all of a sudden I heard and felt this woosh of air over my head. I looked forward to see that the Pileated had just flown about two feet over my head and landed about 12 ft away three ft off the ground. The bird than spent about 25 minutes foraging on this tree going into the ground many times and allowing very close approaches. The bird than proceeded to move intermittently between trees staying very close to the base of the trunk each time! As if things couldn’t get more incredible, on my return trip, Sean found the male exact sting a nest which was amazing!!

Observation Details: The first three photos show this male PIWO foraging on the trunk of a dead Loblolly Pine tree, as photographed from the door of my A-frame cabin on the banks of Holmes Creek.  This is the tree that Hurricane Michael blew over in October 2018, but it got hung up in another pine, to keep it from falling.  It is/was leaning at a 45 degree angle.  It did die over the intervening 17 months.  Instead of having it cut down, clear to the ground, I left about 30 feet for the Pileateds.  The PIWOs took to it immediately after I had the upper canopy of the pine removed.  I was so grateful I left the bottom 1/3 of the tree for them!  In the 55-second sound recording, made with just my iPhone’s voice recorder app, you can hear not only the drumming of a Pileated and a Red-bellied Woodpecker, but you can also hear the wing sound of a flushing Mourning Dove.  Other birds on the recording: Carolina Wren, Northern Cardinal, Red-shouldered Hawk, Yellow-bellied Sapsucker, American Crow, American Goldfinch, Blue-gray Gnatcatcher, and the scold of a Blue-headed Vireo, for a total of at least 11 species.

I was walking on a trail when I heard a loud Pileated behind me.  I turned around to see this guy about 30 feet away barreling down the trail directly at me at eye level.  It startled me a good bit.  The bird swerved at the last second and landed on a very nearby tree and I got off one quick shot before he realized he wasn’t comfortable being that close to me and took off calling loudly again.  The picture isn’t a good shot but it certainly captured the fact that he was as surprised as I was.
